]]\n|votes = 25,263\n|percentage = 47.2\n|change = +3.7\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party = Conservative Party (UK)\n|candidate = Dan Watkins\n|votes = 22,421\n|percentage = 41.9\n|change = +3.4\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party = Green Party of England and Wales\n|candidate = Esther Obiri-Darko \n|votes = 2,201\n|percentage = 4.1\n|change = +2.9\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party = Liberal Democrats (UK)\n|candidate = Philip Ling<ref>http://www.libdems.org.uk/general_election_candidates#London</ref>\n|votes = 2,107\n|percentage = 3.9\n|change = \u221210.9\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party = UK Independence Party\n|candidate = Przemek Skwirczy\u0144ski\n|votes = 1,537\n|percentage = 2.9\n|change = +1.6\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n|votes = 2,842\n|percentage = 5.3\n|change = +0.3\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n|votes = 53,529\n|percentage = 69.7\n|change = +1.1\n}}\n{{Election box registered electors|\n |reg. electors = 76,782\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link|\n|winner = Labour Party (UK)\n|swing = +0.1\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of United Kingdom by-elections (2010\u2013present)]]\n\n{{By-elections to the 56th UK Parliament}}\n\n[[Category:2016 elections in the United Kingdom|Tooting by-election]]\n[[Category:2016 in London|Tooting by-election]]\n[[Category:By-elections to the Parliament of the United Kingdom in London constituencies]]\n[[Category:June 2016 events in the United Kingdom|Tooting by-election]]\n", "name_user": "Littlemonday", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removed a link that linked to this page", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2016_Tooting_by-election"}
{"title_page": "Alex Iwobi", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=January 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|name           = Alex Iwobi one knobi\n|image          = Alex Iwobi 2019.jpg \n|image_size     = 200\n|caption        = Iwobi playing for [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in 2019\n|fullname       = Alexander Chuka Iwobioneknobi<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cafonline.com/en-us/competitions/qcan2017/TeamDetails/playerdetails?CompetitionPlayerId=9PLZLwyxIAmO73W9ZXXjW%2BL7u%2BTkaxtkS8A%2BGq2VhgcjWLxL024Qcwv7fD7Lj%2FAV |title=Player details |publisher=Confederation of African Football |accessdate=26 January 2017}}</ref>\n|birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1996|5|3|df=y}}\n|birth_place    = [[Lagos]], Nigeria\n|height         = 1.80 m<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/players/4717/Alex-Iwobi/overview |title=Alex Iwobi: Overview |publisher=Premier League |accessdate=2 January 2019}}</ref>\n|position       = [[Midfielder#Winger|Winger]] / [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n|currentclub    = [[Everton F.C.|Everton]]\n|clubnumber     = 17\n|youthyears1    = 2004\u20132015\n|youthclubs1    = [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]\n|years1         = 2015\u20132019\n|clubs1         = [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]\n|caps1          = 100\n|goals1         = 11\n|years2         = 2019\u2013\n|clubs2         = [[Everton F.C.|Everton]]\n|caps2          = 18<!--LEAGUE ONLY, NO LIVE UPDATES, DON'T FORGET TO UPDATE club-update PARAMETER-->\n|goals2         = 1\n|nationalyears1 = 2011\u20132012\n|nationalteam1  = [[England national under-16 football team|England U16]]\n|nationalcaps1  = 7\n|nationalgoals1 = 1\n|nationalyears2 = 2013\n|nationalteam2  = [[England national under-17 football team|England U17]]\n|nationalcaps2  = 3\n|nationalgoals2 = 0\n|nationalyears3 = 2013\n|nationalteam3  = [[England national under-18 football team|England U18]]\n|nationalcaps3  = 1\n|nationalgoals3 = 0\n|nationalyears4 = 2015\u2013\n|nationalteam4  = [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]]\n|nationalcaps4  = 40\n|nationalgoals4 = 7\n|club-update    = 18:58, 23 February 2020 (UTC)\n|ntupdate       = 20:50, 17 November 2019 (UTC)\n}}\n'''Alexander Chuka Iwobi''' ({{IPAc-en|\u026a|\u02c8|w|o\u028a|b|i}} {{respell|ih|WOH|bee}};<ref>{{Citation |last=Arsenal |title=Arsenal: Introducing Alex Iwobi |date=22 May 2014 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G54QflUOpKo&t=22s |accessdate=17 November 2017}}</ref> born 3 May 1996) is a Nigerian professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]] for {{English football updater|Everton}} club [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] and the [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria national team]].\n\nHe began his career at [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]], making 149 appearances and scoring 15 goals, and winning the [[FA Cup]] in 2017. In August 2019, he transferred to Everton for an initial \u00a328 million fee.\n\nIwobi represented England up to [[England national under-18 football team|under-18]] level. He made his senior international debut for Nigeria in October 2015, and was part of their squads at the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] and [[2019 Africa Cup of Nations]], coming third at the latter.\n\n==Early and personal life==\nIwobi was born in [[Lagos]] before moving to England at the age of four, following a brief stay in Turkey,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Taylor |first1=Daniel |title=How Arsenal's Alex Iwobi became England's loss and Nigeria's gain |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2016/mar/26/arsenal-alex-iwobi-england-nigeria |accessdate=10 April 2016 |newspaper=The Guardian |date=26 March 2016}}</ref><ref name = \"AFC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.arsenal.com/academy/players/alex-iwobi |title=Profile |accessdate=11 October 2015 |publisher=Arsenal F.C.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Lawrence |first1=Amy |title=Alex Iwobi: 'I did extra training. My mum made me do kick-ups in the living room' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/dec/09/alex-iwobi-arsenal-extra-sessions |accessdate=6 November 2018 |newspaper=The Guardian |date=9 December 2016}}</ref> and grew up in [[London Borough of Newham|Newham]], London.<ref name = \"indy\"/> His maternal uncle is former professional footballer [[Jay-Jay Okocha]].<ref name=\"AFC\" /><ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47988402|title=Arsenal's Alex Iwobi hoping to emulate uncle Jay-Jay Okocha's success|date=19 April 2019|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\n===Arsenal===\n[[File:Alex Iwobi 20150814.jpg|thumb|upright|Iwobi (right) playing for [[Arsenal F.C. Reserves|Arsenal U21s]] in 2015]]\n[[File:Alex Iwobi (24109638313) (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|Iwobi with Arsenal, 2016]]\nIwobi joined [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] while still at primary school,<ref name=\"Alex Iwobi signs new contract\">{{cite news |url=http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/20151006/alex-iwobi-signs-new-contract |title=Alex Iwobi signs new contract |date=6 October 2015 |accessdate=25 March 2016 |publisher=Arsenal F.C.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/arsenal/11915430/Who-is-Alex-Iwobi.html |title=Arsenal tie down young Nigerian forward Alex Iwobi to a new long term contract: but who is he? |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref> in 2004,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.90min.com/posts/6247986-alex-iwobi-reveals-how-close-he-was-to-leaving-arsenal-after-talks-with-premier-league-pair|title=Alex Iwobi Reveals How Close He Was to Leaving Arsenal After Talks With Premier League Pair|date=15 December 2018|website=90min.com}}</ref> and was nearly released by the club at the age of 14 and again at the age of 16.<ref name = \"indy\">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/arsenal-news-alex-iwobi-emirates-gunners-a7362431.html|title=How Alex Iwobi avoided an Emirates exit to become Arsenal's breakout star|date=14 October 2016|website=The Independent}}</ref>\n\nHe was first involved in a [[first-team]] match as an unused [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] in a [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] match against [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] on 25 September 2013.<ref>{{cite web |title=Results/matches: 2013/14 |url=http://www.soccerbase.com/teams/team.sd?team_id=142&teamTabs=results&season_id=143 |website=Soccerbase |publisher=Centurycomm |accessdate=25 March 2016}}</ref> He signed a long-term contract with Arsenal in October 2015.<ref name=\"Alex Iwobi signs new contract\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.premierleague.com/en-gb/players/profile.overview.html/alex-iwobi-2 |title=Profile |accessdate=13 October 2015 |publisher=Premier League}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 October 2015, Iwobi made his first-team debut for the club, starting in a 3\u20130 defeat to [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]] in the Round of 16 of the League Cup.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34654548 |title=Arsene Wenger 'used too many senior players' in League Cup exit |date=28 October 2015 |accessdate=1 November 2015 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34578025 |title=Sheffield Wednesday 3\u20130 Arsenal |date=27 October 2015 |accessdate=1 November 2015 |author=Luke Reddy |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> He made his Premier League debut four days later in a 3\u20130 win against [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]] at the [[Liberty Stadium]], as a stoppage time substitute for [[Mesut \u00d6zil]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34623949 |title=Swansea City 0\u20133 Arsenal |date=31 October 2015 |accessdate=1 November 2015 |author=Dafydd Pritchard |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> Iwobi made his [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] debut as an 85th-minute substitute in a 5\u20131 defeat against Bayern Munich.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/34892626 |title=Bayern Munich 5\u20131 Arsenal |date=4 November 2015 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> Iwobi started in the first team for the [[2015\u201316 FA Cup]] 3rd and 4th round home wins against [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] and [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] respectively.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Critchley |first1=Mark |title=Arsenal vs Sunderland team news: Alex Iwobi handed first-team chance, Petr Cech starts in goal |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/fa-league-cups/arsenal-vs-sunderland-team-news-alex-iwobi-handed-first-team-chance-petr-cech-starts-in-goal-a6803886.html |accessdate=1 February 2016 |newspaper=The Independent |date=9 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Hytner |first1=David |title=Ars\u00e8ne Wenger makes England quip over Arsenal's in-form Alex Iwobi |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/jan/31/arsene-wenger-england-arsenal-alex-iwobi-roy-hodgson-burnley-fa-cup |accessdate=1 February 2016 |newspaper=The Guardian |date=31 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nAfter getting a first Champions League start in a 3\u20131 away defeat to Barcelona,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/35814925 |title=Champions League: Barcelona 3\u20131 Arsenal (agg 5\u20131) |date=16 March 2016 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> Iwobi went on to score two goals in his first two Premier League starts in wins against [[Everton F.C.|Everton]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/35792188 |title=Everton 0\u20132 Arsenal |date=19 March 2016 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> and [[Watford F.C.|Watford]], respectively.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/35902639 |title=Arsenal 4\u20130 Watford |date=2 April 2016 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\nIn the following season, Iwobi changed his squad number from 45 to 17, after [[Alexis S\u00e1nchez]] took number 7 from the departing [[Tom\u00e1\u0161 Rosick\u00fd]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espnfc.com/english-premier-league/story/2881382/granit-xhaka-to-wear-arsenal-no-16-shirt-alex-iwobi-to-wear-no-17 |title=Granit Xhaka to wear Arsenal No. 16 shirt, Alex Iwobi takes over No. 17 |date=27 May 2016 |publisher=ESPN FC}}</ref> He went on to feature throughout Arsenal's victorious [[2016\u201317 FA Cup|FA Cup campaign of 2016\u201317]], winning 2\u20131 against [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] in the [[2016-17 FA Cup|final]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dede |first1=Steve |title=Arsenal star is an FA Cup winner |url=http://pulse.ng/sports/football/alex-iwobi-wins-fa-cup-title-with-arsenal-id6746129.html |accessdate=29 May 2017 |website=pulse.ng |date=28 May 2017}}</ref> He achieved further success with Arsenal in the [[2017 FA Community Shield|2017 Community Shield]], in which Arsenal beat Chelsea on penalties.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.goal.com/en-au/amp/news/lets-keep-it-going-iwobi-lauds-arsenal-after-community/1gyizgop73z4s1v9kp2jfxd23j |title='Let's keep it going' \u2013 Iwobi lauds ARSENAL after Community Shield Triumph |website=Goal.com}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, a video was released that allegedly showed Iwobi at a late-night party 36 hours before a match.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42617708|title=Alex Iwobi: Arsenal forward faces fine over pre-match party claims|date=5 May 2018|accessdate=1 February 2019|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> In May 2018, after Arsenal manager [[Ars\u00e8ne Wenger]] announced he would be leaving the club, Iwobi described him as an \"inspiration\" and stated it was sad but exciting.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43988015 |title=Nigeria's Alex Iwobi says Wenger exit 'sad' and 'exciting' |date=3 May 2018 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2018, he signed a new long-term contract with the club, reportedly until 2023.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45060242|title=Alex Iwobi: Arsenal midfielder signs new 'long-term' deal|date=3 August 2018|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, Iwobi was the subject of alleged racism from Indian actress [[Esha Gupta]], an Arsenal ambassador.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-india-47042681|title=Esha Gupta: Has Instagram exposed everyday racism in India?|date=1 February 2019|accessdate=1 February 2019|publisher=BBC News}}</ref> In July 2019, after the [[2019 Africa Cup of Nations]], he said he was looking forward to returning to club football with Arsenal.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49070902|title=Nigeria's Alex Iwobi shifts focus to Arsenal after Nations Cup|date=22 July 2019|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\n===Everton===\nOn 8 August 2019, Iwobi signed a five-year contract with [[Everton F.C.|Everton]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.evertonfc.com/news/1303855/Everton-Seal-Signing-Of-Iwobi |title=Everton Seal Signing of Iwobi |date=8 August 2019 |publisher=Everton F.C.}}</ref>  According to the [[BBC]], Arsenal received a fee of an initial \u00a328 million, rising to \u00a334 million with potential add-ons.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/49282957|title=Alex Iwobi: Everton sign Arsenal forward in five-year deal worth up to \u00a334m|date=8 August 2019|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\nFifteen days after signing, Iwobi made his debut as a substitute for the final half-hour in place of [[Gylfi Sigur\u00f0sson]] in a 2\u20130 loss at Aston Villa.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kirkbride |first1=Phil |title=Everton new-boy Alexi Iwobi explains Marco Silva's tactical instructions ahead of debut |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/everton-new-boy-alexi-iwobi-16811240 |accessdate=7 January 2020 |work=Liverpool Echo |date=24 August 2019}}</ref> On 28 August in the second round of the EFL Cup, he scored his first Everton goal in a 4\u20132 win at [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jones |first1=Adam |title=Alex Iwobi's love, a damning statistic broken and other moments missed from Everton's Lincoln win |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/alex-iwobis-love-damning-statistic-16835167 |accessdate=7 January 2020 |work=Liverpool Echo |date=29 August 2019}}</ref> He scored his first league goal on 1 September in a 3\u20132 win over [[Wolverhampton Wanderers]], and was one of two players singled out for praise by manager [[Marco Silva]] afterwards.<ref>{{cite news |title=Marco Silva impressed by two Everton players in Wolves win |url=https://www.football365.com/news/marco-silva-impressed-by-two-everton-players-in-wolves-win |accessdate=7 January 2020 |publisher=Football 365 |date=1 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n[[File:Alex Iwobi-Nigeria.jpg|thumb|150px|Iwobi with [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]] in 2017]]\n\nIwobi started as a youth international for England, with whom he won the 2011 [[Victory Shield]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thefa.com/england/all-teams/players/i/alex-iwobi |title=Profile |accessdate=11 October 2015 |publisher=The Football Association}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2016/mar/26/arsenal-alex-iwobi-england-nigeria |title=How Arsenal's Alex Iwobi became England's loss and Nigeria's gain |date=26 March 2016 |newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref><ref name=Trophy /> Iwobi went on though to play for [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]]. He made his senior debut for the Super Eagles on 8 October 2015, replacing [[Ahmed Musa (footballer)|Ahmed Musa]] in the 57th minute of a 2\u20130 friendly defeat to [[DR Congo national football team|DR Congo]] in [[Vis\u00e9]], Belgium.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34497630 |title=Arsenal's Alex Iwobi encouraged by Nigeria opportunity |date=10 October 2015 |accessdate=11 October 2015 |author=Oluwashina Okeleji |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\nHe was selected by Nigeria for their 35-man provisional squad for the [[2016 Summer Olympics]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36623763 |title=Kelechi Iheanacho included in Nigeria's Olympics squad |date=24 June 2016 |accessdate=25 June 2016 |author=Oluwashina Okeleji |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> He was not a part of the 18-man final squad.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/mensolympic/teams/team=1889763/players.html |title=Olympic Football Tournament Rio 2016 - Nigeria |publisher=FIFA}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2017 Iwobi pulled out of Nigeria's squad for that month's World Cup qualifiers due to injury.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41068525 |title=Iwobi ruled out of Nigeria's World Cup qualifiers against Cameroon |date=27 August 2017 |accessdate=31 August 2017 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> In October 2017, Iwobi scored for Nigeria in a 1\u20130 win over Zambia to secure the Super Eagles a spot in the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] in Russia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://punchng.com/iwobi-sends-nigeria-to-russia-2018/|title=Iwobi sends Nigeria to Russia 2018}}</ref> He was named in Nigeria's 23-man squad for the competition and featured in all three games as the Super Eagles were knocked out in the group stage.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44346451|title=World Cup 2018: Arsenal's Iwobi in Nigeria's 23-man squad|date=3 June 2018|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/players/player/395533/|title=2018 FIFA World Cup Russia\u2122 - Players - Alex IWOBI - Alex Iwobi - FIFA.com|last=FIFA.com|website=www.fifa.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-09-21}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, he said he wanted to emulate his uncle Jay-Jay Okocha by winning the Africa Cup of Nations.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/> He was included in Nigeria's squad for the 2019 tournament.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en-ie/news/afcon-will-be-like-a-war-declares-nigerias-alex-iwobi/1p7yxjqd3hsu6161slwsotf7pp|title=Afcon will be like a war, declares Nigeria's Alex Iwobi &#124; Goal.com|website=www.goal.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en/news/afcon-2019-players-alex-iwobi-the-rise-of-series/1h15jxevwvsl011juivezrm2hg|title=Afcon 2019 players: Alex Iwobi - The Rise Of Series &#124; Goal.com|website=www.goal.com}}</ref> At the tournament he said he would ignore the labelling of Nigeria as favourites.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48970807|title=Africa Cup of Nations 2019: Nigeria will ignore favourites tag, says Iwobi|date=12 July 2019|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> After the tournament he said he was looking forward to returning to club football with Arsenal.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|match played 23 February 2020}}\n\n{| class=wikitable style=text-align:center\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[FA Cup]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[EFL Cup|League Cup]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|Europe\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|[[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]\n|[[2015\u201316 Arsenal F.C. season|2015\u201316]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|72651|2015|accessdate=30 August 2019}}</ref>\n|[[Premier League]]\n|13||2||5||0||1||0||2{{efn|name=UCL|Appearances in [[UEFA Champions League]]}}||0||0||0||21||2\n|-\n|[[2016\u201317 Arsenal F.C. season|2016\u201317]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|72651|2016|accessdate=30 August 2019}}</ref>\n|Premier League\n|26||3||3||0||2||0||7{{efn|name=UCL}}||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||38||4\n|-\n|[[2017\u201318 Arsenal F.C. season|2017\u201318]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|72651|2017|accessdate=30 August 2019}}</ref>\n|Premier League\n|26||3||1||0||5||0||6{{efn|name=UEL|Appearances in [[UEFA Europa League]]}}||0||1{{efn|Appearance in [[FA Community Shield]]}}||0||39||3\n|-\n|[[2018\u201319 Arsenal F.C. season|2018\u201319]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|72651|2018|accessdate=30 August 2019}}</ref>\n|Premier League\n|35||3||2||1||3||0||11{{efn|name=UEL}}||2||0||0||51||6\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total\n!100!!11!!11!!1!!11!!0!!26!!3!!1!!0!!149!!15\n|-\n|[[Everton F.C.|Everton]]\n|[[2019\u201320 Everton F.C. season|2019\u201320]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|72651|2019|accessdate=30 August 2019}}</ref>\n|Premier League\n|18||1||0||0||4||1||colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014||22||2\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career total\n!118!!12!!11!!1!!15!!1!!26!!3!!1!!0!!171!!17\n|}\n\n{{notelist}}\n\n===International===\n{{updated|match played 17 November 2019}}<ref name=\"NFT\">{{NFT player|pid=60750|accessdate=30 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=wikitable style=text-align:center\n|+ Appearances and goals by national team and year\n|-\n!National team!!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|[[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]]\n|2015||2||0\n|-\n|2016||6||1\n|-\n|2017||5||3\n|-\n|2018||12||1\n|-\n|2019||15||2\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total!!40!!7\n|}\n\n===International goals===\n:''As of match played 17 November 2019. Scores and results list Nigeria's goal tally first.''<ref name=\"NFT\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! No !! Date !! Venue !! Opponent !! Score !! Result !! Competition\n|-\n| align=center | 1. || 9 October 2016 || [[Levy Mwanawasa Stadium]], Ndola, Zambia || rowspan=2 | {{fb|ZAM}} || align=center | 1\u20130 || align=center | <center>2\u20131</center> || rowspan=2 | [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 CAF Third Round|2018 FIFA World Cup qualification]]\n|-\n| align=center | 2. || 7 October 2017 || [[Godswill Akpabio International Stadium]], Uyo, Nigeria || align=center | 1\u20130 || align=center | 1\u20130\n|-\n| align=center | 3. || rowspan=2 | 14 November 2017 || rowspan=2 | [[Krasnodar Stadium]], Krasnodar, Russia || rowspan=2 | {{fb|ARG}} || align=center | 2\u20132 || rowspan=2 | <center>4\u20132</center>|| rowspan=3 | [[Exhibition game#Association football|Friendly]]\n|-\n| align=center | 4. || align=center | 4\u20132\n|-\n| align=center | 5. || 2 June 2018 || [[Wembley Stadium]], London, England || {{fb|ENG}} || align=center | 1\u20132 || <center>1\u20132</center>\n|-\n| align=ce