{indent|3}}{{cite news|last=Arunachalam|first=Jayashree|title=Tale of epic grandeur|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/dance/tale-of-epic-grandeur/article26008.ece|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160219135057/http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/dance/tale-of-epic-grandeur/article26008.ece|archivedate=19 February 2016|accessdate=12 December 2015|agency=[[The Hindu]]|date=28 September 2009|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2009\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[The Tempest]]''\n| [[Prospero]]\n| Malayalam\n| {{sort|Kumar|[[T. K. Rajeev Kumar]]}}\n| [[Jose Thomas Performing Arts Centre]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/mohanlal-to-play-prospero/article656373.ece | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160219140551/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/mohanlal-to-play-prospero/article656373.ece | archivedate=19 February 2016 | title=Mohanlal to play Prospero | work=[[The Hindu]] | date=29 January 2009 | accessdate=10 December 2015 | last=Manmadhan | first=Prema |url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2010\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Vikram\u014drva\u015b\u012byam]]''\n| [[Pururavas]]\n| Sanskrit\n| {{sort|Panicker|[[Kavalam Narayana Panicker]]}}\n| [[Ujjain]], [[Madhya Pradesh]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/theatre/mohanlal-to-return-to-stage-with-kalidasas-play/article258115.ece | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160219140004/http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/theatre/mohanlal-to-return-to-stage-with-kalidasas-play/article258115.ece | archivedate=19 February 2016 | title=Mohanlal to return to stage with Kalidasa's play | work=[[The Hindu]] | date=19 March 2010 | last=PTI|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2015\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Naga''\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Narrator''\n| Malayalam\n| {{sort|Suveeran|[[Suveeran]]}}\n| Parish Hall, [[St. George Church, Kalady]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/kochi/Mohanlal-Mukesh-to-Set-Stage-Afire-with-Naga/2015/08/08/article2963127.ece | title=Mohanlal, Mukesh to Set Stage Afire with 'Naga' | work=[[The New Indian Express]] | date=8 August 2015 | accessdate=10 December 2015 | last=Kallungal |first=Dhinesh | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222083204/http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/kochi/Mohanlal-Mukesh-to-Set-Stage-Afire-with-Naga/2015/08/08/article2963127.ece | archivedate=22 December 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Radio drama==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"margin-right: 0;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Role\n! scope=\"col\" | Broadcaster\n! scope=\"col\" | Director\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | {{abbr|Ref.|Reference(s)}}\n|-\n| 1987\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Jeevanulla Prathimakal''\n| {{Unknown}}\n| [[All India Radio]]\n| {{sort|Chandran|Satheesh Chandran}}\n| Re-broadcast on 27 September 2010\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite web | last = Varma | first = Sivadas | url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/kerala/article489054.ece | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151225042658/http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/kerala/article489054.ece | archivedate=25 December 2015 | title=Go back in time with radio plays | publisher=[[The New Indian Express]]|date= 21 September 2010|accessdate= 21 September 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of awards and nominations received by Mohanlal|Awards and nominations received by Mohanlal]]\n* [[List of songs recorded by Mohanlal|Songs recorded by Mohanlal]]\n{{Portal bar|Arts|Biography|Film|India|Radio|Theatre}}\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|25em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikimedia|collapsible=true|wikt=no|d=Q13635345|v=no|b=no|c=Category:Mohanlal}}\n* {{official website}}\n* {{IMDb name|0482320|Mohanlal}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{Mohanlal|state=expanded}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mohanlal}}\n[[Category:Mohanlal]]\n[[Category:Male actor filmographies]]\n[[Category:Indian filmographies]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=February 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2016}}\n\n[[File:Padmabhushan Mohanlal.jpg|thumb|upright=1.0|alt=|Mohanlal receiving Padmabhushan 2020]]\n\n[[Mohanlal]] is an Indian actor, director, producer, and playback singer who has starred in both [[Blockbuster (entertainment)|blockbuster]] and [[Art film|art house]] films.<ref>{{cite web|last=Warrier|first=Shobha|title='I celebrate whether a film is a hit or a flop'|url=http://www.rediff.com/entertai/apr/04mohn.htm|publisher=[[Rediff.com]]|accessdate=27 March 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107034816/http://www.rediff.com/entertai/apr/04mohn.htm|archivedate=7 November 2014|date=4 April 1997|url-status=live}}</ref> During his career, he has appeared in more than 345 feature films, primarily in [[Malayalam cinema]], and also in [[Bollywood]], [[Tamil cinema|Tamil]], [[Telugu cinema|Telugu]], and [[Kannada cinema|Kannada]] films.<ref name=34films>{{cite news|last=James|first=Anu|title=Mohanlal Turns 55; Notable Facts about 'the Complete Actor' [PHOTOS]|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/mohanlal-turns-55-notable-facts-about-complete-actor-photos-633117|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151223202135/http://www.ibtimes.co.in/mohanlal-turns-55-notable-facts-about-complete-actor-photos-633117|archivedate=23 December 2015|accessdate=1 January 2016|work=[[International Business Times]]|date=21 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> In 1978, when he was 18, he started acting with a minor comedic role in the unreleased film ''[[Thiranottam]]'', before making screen debut in 1980 as antagonist in the [[romance film]] ''[[Manjil Virinja Pookkal]]''.<ref name=\"ActingAlone\">{{cite web|last=Warrier|first=Shobha|title='Life is not about acting alone'|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2003/sep/03mohanlal.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151216230036/http://www.rediff.com/movies/2003/sep/03mohanlal.htm|archivedate=16 December 2015|publisher=[[Rediff.com]]|accessdate=1 January 2016|date=3 September 2003|url-status=live}}</ref> His portrayal of Narendran, a sadistic husband, received recognition and the film developed a [[cult film|cult]] status in Malayalam cinema.<ref name=team48>{{cite web|last=Ranjitha|title=Team of 48|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/1998/sep/01hari1.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040318112351/http://www.rediff.com/movies/1998/sep/01hari1.htm|archivedate=18 March 2004|publisher=[[Rediff.com]]|accessdate=1 January 2016|date=1 September 1998|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Moviebuzz (Sify)|title=Mohanlal & Poornima are together again!|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/mohanlal-poornima-are-together-again-news-malayalam-nfoqliiejfbsi.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160219153421/http://www.sify.com/movies/mohanlal-poornima-are-together-again-news-malayalam-nfoqliiejfbsi.html|archivedate=19 February 2016|publisher=[[Sify.com]]|accessdate=1 January 2016|date=14 May 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Subsequently, Mohanlal was cast as the antagonist in many films. His first positive role was in ''[[Padayottam]]'' (1982), the first [[70 mm film]] in Malayalam.<ref name=team48/> It was 1983's ''[[Aattakalasam]]'' that gave him stardom.<ref>{{cite news|last=Menon|first=Neelima|title=Can Mohanlal And Mammootty Keep Up With New-Gen Malayalam Films?|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.in/entry/can-mohanlal-mammootty-keep-up-with-new-gen-malayalam-films_in_5d32e125e4b004b6adb05aa6|accessdate=23 July 2019|work=[[HuffPost]]|date=23 July 2019}}</ref> In 1984 he starred in ''[[Poochakkoru Mookkuthi]]'', a comedy film whose success triggered a trend and popularised the genre in the 1980s.<ref name=25years>{{cite web|last=Warrier|first=Shobha|title=25 years, 25 landmarks|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2003/sep/03mohan1.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160121020441/http://www.rediff.com/movies/2003/sep/03mohan1.htm|archivedate=21 January 2016|publisher=[[Rediff.com]]|accessdate=1 January 2016|date=3 September 2003|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Times News Network|title=Priyan's remake Darshan|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2007-05-12/news/28443490_1_priyadarshan-remakes-hindi-film|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222161539/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2007-05-12/news/28443490_1_priyadarshan-remakes-hindi-film|archivedate=22 December 2015|accessdate=1 January 2016|work=[[The Economic Times]]|date=12 May 2007|url-status=live}}</ref> In an early critically acclaimed performance, Mohanlal played an [[antihero]] in the [[I. V. Sasi]]-directed thriller ''[[Uyarangalil]]'' (1984).<ref name=MT84/> In the same year, he co-founded Casino Films,{{efn|Mohanlal co-founded Casino Films with [[I. V. Sasi]], [[Seema (actress)|Seema]], [[Mammootty]], and Century Kochumon.<ref name=casino/>}} a motion picture production company which later produced his popular comedies ''[[Gandhinagar 2nd Street]]'' (1986) and ''[[Nadodikkattu]]'' (1987).<ref name=casino>{{cite news|last=N|first=Sethumadhavan|title=In Search of Greener Pastures|url=http://www.bangaloremirror.com/entertainment/south-masala/In-search-of-greener-pastures/articleshow/48228444.cms|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222095311/http://www.bangaloremirror.com/entertainment/south-masala/In-search-of-greener-pastures/articleshow/48228444.cms|archivedate=22 December 2015|accessdate=31 December 2015|work=[[Bangalore Mirror]]|date=26 July 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAs a [[playback singer]], Mohanlal contributed his first song \"Sindhoora Megham\" to ''[[Onnanam Kunnil Oradi Kunnil]]'' (1985).<ref name=25years/> In 1986, he established a career record by starring in 34 films in one year.<ref name=34films/> Also in 1986, he became the youngest winner for [[Kerala State Film Award for Best Actor]] at age 26 for the comedy drama ''[[T. P. Balagopalan M.A.]]'',<ref name=25years/> a record he held until 2006.<ref>{{cite news|last=Vasudevan|first=Aishwarya|title=Prithviraj: Lesser known facts|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/malayalam/movies/Prithviraj-Lesser-known-facts/photostory/48958589.cms|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160219154704/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/malayalam/movies/Prithviraj-Lesser-known-facts/photostory/48958589.cms|archivedate=19 February 2016|accessdate=4 January 2016|work=[[The Times of India]]|date=10 January 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> The same year he co-founded Cheers Films, a second production company.{{efn|Mohanlal co-founded Cheers Films with Century Kochumon.<ref name=\"cheersfilms\">{{cite news | url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/malayalam/movies/Mohanlal-Lesser-known-facts/photostory/48683869.cms | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160219131054/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/malayalam/movies/Mohanlal-Lesser-known-facts/photostory/48683869.cms | archivedate=19 February 2016 | title=Mohanlal: Lesser known facts | work=[[The Times of India]] | date=12 November 2012 | accessdate=12 December 2015 | last=Vasudevan | first=Aishwarya |url-status=live}}</ref>}} Mohanlal's stardom catapulted with the success of the crime drama ''[[Rajavinte Makan]]'' (1986).<ref>{{cite news|last=PTI|title=Will do a Hindi film only if it's irresistible: Mohanlal|url=http://www.firstpost.com/bollywood/will-do-a-hindi-film-only-if-its-irresistible-mohanlal-280540.html|accessdate=4 March 2016|work=[[Firstpost]]|date=19 April 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304151910/http://www.firstpost.com/bollywood/will-do-a-hindi-film-only-if-its-irresistible-mohanlal-280540.html|archivedate=4 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> In ''[[Irupatham Noottandu]]'' (1987), he portrayed mobster Sagar Alias Jacky {{mdash}} which became a cult figure in crime dramas ever since its release.<ref>{{cite news|last=Onmanorama Desk|title=Sagar Alias Jacky: Mohanlal joins Dubsmash craze|url=http://english.manoramaonline.com/entertainment/entertainment-news/mohanlal-joins-dubsmash-craze.html|accessdate=25 March 2016|work=[[Malayala Manorama]]|date=18 June 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151213014353/http://english.manoramaonline.com/entertainment/entertainment-news/mohanlal-joins-dubsmash-craze.html|archivedate=13 December 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> His [[tragicomedy]] ''[[Chithram]]'' (1988) ran continuously for 58 weeks in one theatre, a record still unbroken in Malayalam cinema.<ref name=\"milestone\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/milestones-in-mohanlal-s-career-news-malayalam-kkfv4xbabjgsi.html|title=Milestones in Mohanlal's career|date=21 May 2005|publisher=[[Sify.com]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160204162519/http://www.sify.com/movies/milestones-in-mohanlal-s-career-news-malayalam-kkfv4xbabjgsi.html|archivedate=4 February 2016|accessdate=5 January 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> In 1989, his performance in ''[[Kireedam (1989 film)|Kireedam]]'' earned him a [[National Film Award \u2013 Special Mention (Feature Film)|Special Jury Mention]] at the [[37th National Film Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Warrier|first=Shobha|title=Special: The A-Z of Malayalam cinema|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-south-a-z-of-malayalam-cinema/20120420.htm#11|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131019192242/http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-south-a-z-of-malayalam-cinema/20120420.htm#11|archivedate=19 October 2013|publisher=[[Rediff.com]]|accessdate=5 January 2016|date=20 April 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 1990, Mohanlal founded his own film production company, [[Pranavam Arts International|Pranavam Arts]].<ref name=25years/> Its debut, musical thriller ''[[His Highness Abdullah]]'', garnered critical acclaim and became the year's highest-grossing film.<ref>{{cite news|last=Vasudevan|first=Aishwarya|title=Musical hits of Malayalam film industry|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/malayalam/movies/Musical-hits-of-Malayalam-film-industry/photostory/48522892.cms|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160219154005/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/malayalam/movies/Musical-hits-of-Malayalam-film-industry/photostory/48522892.cms|archivedate=19 February 2016|accessdate=24 January 2016|work=[[The Times of India]]|date=24 July 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> His second production, ''[[Bharatham]]'' (1991), earned him the [[National Film Award for Best Actor]] and ''[[Forbes India]]'' included it on its list of \"25 Greatest Acting Performances in Indian Cinema\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Prasad|first1=Shishir| last2=Ramnath|first2=N.S.|last3= Mitter|first3=Sohini|title=Forbes India Magazine - 25 Greatest Acting Performances of Indian Cinema|url=http://forbesindia.com/article/100-years-of-indian-cinema/25-greatest-acting-performances-of-indian-cinema/35125/0|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160112014841/http://forbesindia.com/article/100-years-of-indian-cinema/25-greatest-acting-performances-of-indian-cinema/35125/0|archivedate=12 January 2016|publisher=[[Forbes India]]|accessdate=24 January 2016|date=27 April 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> His spiritual fantasy, ''[[Guru (1997 film)|Guru]]'' (1997), was the first Malayalam film submitted by India for the American [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film]].<ref>{{cite news|last=IBN LIVE|title=From 'Saaransh' to 'Barfi': India's past Oscar entries in Foreign Language Film category|url=http://www.ibnlive.com/photogallery/movies/from-saaransh-to-barfi-indias-past-oscar-entries-in-foreign-language-film-category-854695.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160323110433/http://www.ibnlive.com/photogallery/movies/from-saaransh-to-barfi-indias-past-oscar-entries-in-foreign-language-film-category-854695.html|archivedate=23 March 2016|accessdate=6 February 2016|work=[[IBN Live]]|date=23 September 2012|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 1997, he received critical praise for his first leading role in a non-Malayalam film\u2014the [[Mani Ratnam]]-directed Tamil film ''[[Iruvar]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Srinivasan|first=Pavithra|title=Mohanlal in Iruvar|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-south-best-performances-in-mani-ratnam-films/20100614.htm#1|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106081325/http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-south-best-performances-in-mani-ratnam-films/20100614.htm#1|archivedate=6 November 2015|publisher=[[Rediff.com]]|accessdate=7 February 2016|date=14 June 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[Vanaprastham]]'', which was screened at the [[Un Certain Regard]] section in the [[1999 Cannes Film Festival]], earned him the National Film Awards for Best Actor and Best Film (Producer).<ref name=milestone/><ref>{{cite news|last=Dhingra|first=Manisha|title=The History of India at Cannes|url=http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/the-history-of-india-at-cannes-639287|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150912153645/http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/the-history-of-india-at-cannes-639287|archivedate=12 September 2015|accessdate=7 February 2016|work=[[NDTV]]|date=14 May 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, Mohanlal's action drama, ''[[Narasimham (film)|Narasimham]]'', became the highest-grossing Malayalam film at the time. His character Induchoodan has since attracted a cult following.<ref>{{cite web|last=Vikram|first=Raj|title='Narasimham' to return after 15 years.|url=http://www.metromatinee.com/news-articles/narasimham-to-return-after-15-years-9681|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150107140546/http://www.metromatinee.com/news-articles/narasimham-to-return-after-15-years-9681|archivedate=7 January 2015|accessdate=8 February 2016|date=21 October 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2001, he portrayed [[Karna]] in his theatrical debut, ''Karnabharam'', directed by [[Kavalam Narayana Panicker]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Viswanath| first=Chandrakanth|title=Battle for the Lone|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/malayalam/Battle-for-the-Lone/2016/01/20/article3234763.ece|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160215192951/http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/malayalam/Battle-for-the-Lone/2016/01/20/article3234763.ece|archivedate=15 February 2016|accessdate=8 February 2016|work=[[The New Indian Express]]|date=20 January 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2003, he earned an [[International Indian Film Academy Awards|International Indian Film Academy Award]] for [[IIFA Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]] for his role in the [[Bollywood]] film ''[[Company (film)|Company]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Press Trust Of India|title=I have nothing to prove in Bollywood: Mohanlal|url=http://movies.ndtv.com/regional/i-have-nothing-to-prove-in-bollywood-mohanlal-624585|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160215235858/http://movies.ndtv.com/regional/i-have-nothing-to-prove-in-bollywood-mohanlal-624585|archivedate=15 February 2016|accessdate=8 February 2016|work=[[NDTV]]|date=17 April 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2005, he starred in the [[Bejoy Nambiar]]-directed [[short film|short]] [[silent film]] ''[[Reflections (2005 film)|Reflections]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Rajpal|first=Roktim|title=Happy birthday Mohanlal: 7 relatively unknown facts about the megastar's life|url=http://www.ibnlive.com/news/movies/happy-birthday-mohanlal-7-relatively-unknown-facts-about-the-megastars-life-994765.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160128124241/http://www.ibnlive.com/news/movies/happy-birthday-mohanlal-7-relatively-unknown-facts-about-the-megastars-life-994765.html|archivedate=28 January 2016|accessdate=8 February 2016|work=[[IBN Live]]|date=21 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> His critically acclaimed portrayal of an [[Alzheimer's disease|Alzhiemers]] patient in ''[[Thanmathra]]'' (2005) earned him an honorary award from the [[Indian Medical Association]].<ref name=\"MohanlalTelegraph\">{{cite news|last=Jayan|first=T.V.|title=Actors live between the two worlds of 'action' and 'cut'|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1140309/jsp/7days/18061240.jsp|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150708110422/http://www.telegraphindia.com/1140309/jsp/7days/18061240.jsp|archivedate=8 July 2015|accessdate=15 January 2016|work=[[The Telegraph (Calcutta)|The Telegraph]] | location=India |date=9 March 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Territorial Army (India)|Indian Territorial Army]] bestowed him with the honorary rank of [[lieutenant colonel]] for his performance as [[Major Mahadevan]] in the [[war film]] ''[[Keerthi Chakra (film)|Keerthi Chakra]]'' (2006) and its sequel ''[[Kurukshetra (2008 film)|Kurukshetra]]'' (2008).<ref>{{cite news|last=Sai Kiran|first=K. P.|title=Lt Col Mohanlal makes his mark in Territorial Army|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/nation/article141454.ece|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160215191528/http://www.newindianexpress.com/nation/article141454.ece|archivedate=15 February 2016|accessdate=8 February 2016|work=[[The New Indian Express]]|date=20 October 2009|location=[[New Delhi]]|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2008, he starred in ''[[Twenty:20 (film)|Twenty:20]]'', a landmark film which starred almost all actors in the guild of Malayalam film actors {{ndash}} [[Association of Malayalam Movie Artists|AMMA]].<ref>{{cite news|last=V. P|first=Nicy|title=Shaji Kailas Confirms Next Film with Mohanlal and Mammootty|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/shaji-kailas-confirms-next-film-mohanlal-mammootty-610700|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160216110732/http://www.ibtimes.co.in/shaji-kailas-confirms-next-film-mohanlal-mammootty-610700|archivedate=16 February 2016|accessdate=8 February 2016|work=[[International Business Times]]|date=7 October 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[Drishyam]]'' (2013), in which he portrayed an ordinary man, became the highest-grossing Malayalam film of all time.<ref>{{cite news|last=James|first=Anu|title='Drishyam' Director Jeethu Joseph Says He Was Unhappy with Mohanlal Starrer's Hindi Remake Cast|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/drishyam-director-jeethu-joseph-says-he-was-unhappy-mohanlal-starrers-hindi-remake-cast-646005|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160216111310/http://www.ibtimes.co.in/drishyam-director-jeethu-joseph-says-he-was-unhappy-mohanlal-starrers-hindi-remake-cast-646005|archivedate=16 February 2016|accessdate=8 February 2016|work=[[International Business Times]]|date=9 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Pillai|first=Radhika C|title=Mollywood praises Mohanlal for Drishyam's success|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/malayalam/movies/news/Mollywood-praises-Mohanlal-for-Drishyams-success/articleshow/27721249.cms|accessdate=4 March 2016|work=[[The Times of India]]|date=21 December 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304151131/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/malayalam/movies/news/Mollywood-praises-Mohanlal-for-Drishyams-success/articleshow/27721249.cms|archivedate=4 March 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2016, he acted in the title role in the action film ''[[Pulimurugan]];'' it became the highest-grossing Malayalam film ever and is the first Malayalam film to gross over {{INR}}150 crore at the box office.<ref>{{cite news|last=Viswanath|first=Chandrakanth|title=Mohanlal's Pulimurugan breaches the Rs 100 crore mark|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/malayalam/2016/nov/07/mohanlals-pulimurugan-breaches-the-rs-100-crore-mark-1536006--2.html|accessdate=11 November 2016|work=[[The New Indian Express]]|date=7 November 2016}}</ref> In 2019, he acted in [[Prithviraj Sukumaran]]'s directorial ''[[Lucifer (film)|Lucifer]]'', which became the highest-grossing Malayalam film ever, collecting more than 200 crore worldwide. His directorial debut, the 3D film ''[[Barroz: Guardian of D'Gama's Treasure]]'' is in pre-production.\n\n==Films in Malayalam==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Key\n| style=\"background:#ffc;\"| {{dagger|alt=Films that have not yet been released}}\n| Denotes films that have not yet been released\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"margin-right: 0;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Role\n! scope=\"col\" | Director\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | {{abbr|Ref.|Reference(s)}}\n|-\n| 1980\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Manjil Virinja Pookkal]]''\n| Narendran\n| {{sort|Fazil|[[Fazil (director)|Fazil]]}}\n|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite news|last=Express News Service|title=The Camera that Captured a Star|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/malayalam/article387139.ece|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151224195251/http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/malayalam/article387139.ece|archivedate=24 December 2015|accessdate=15 December 2015|work=[[The New Indian Express]]|date=24 April 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1981\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Sanchari]]''\n| {{sort|Sekhar|Dr. Sekhar}}\n| {{sort|Kunchacko|Boban Kunchacko}}  \n|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite news|last=\u0d2d\u0d3e\u0d28\u0d41\u0d2a\u0d4d\u0d30\u0d15\u0d3e\u0d36\u0d4d|title=\u0d38\u0d02\u0d18\u0d1f\u0d4d\u0d1f\u0d28\u0d30\u0d02\u0d17\u0d19\u0d4d\u0d19\u0d33\u0d4d\u200d\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d4d \u0d07\u0d31\u0d19\u0d4d\u0d19\u0d41\u0d2e\u0d4d\u0d2a\u0d4b\u0d33\u0d4d\u200d \u0d1c\u0d2f\u0d7b \u0d15\u0d4a\u0d1f\u0d41\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d24 \u0d06 \u0d09\u0d2a\u0d26\u0d47\u0d36\u0d2e\u0d3e\u0d23\u0d4d \u0d07\u0d2a\u0d4d\u0d2a\u0d4b\u0d34\u0d41\u0d02 \u0d2e\u0d4b\u0d39\u0d28\u0d4d\u200d\u0d32\u0d3e\u0d32\u0d3f\u0d28\u0d4d\u0d31\u0d46 \u0d2e\u0d28\u0d38\u0d4d\u0d38\u0d3f\u0d32\u0d4d\u200d|url=http://www.mathrubhumi.com/movies-music/flashback/jayan-mo